ARIMA Forecasting on Coffee Sales

dat <- read.csv("Coffe_sales.csv")
dat$Date <- as.Date(dat$Date)   


daily <- aggregate(money ~ Date, data = dat, FUN = sum)


y <- ts(daily$money, frequency = 7)

1. Fit ARIMA Model & Explain Output

fit_arima <- auto.arima(y)
summary(fit_arima)
## Series: y 
## ARIMA(2,0,2) with non-zero mean 
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ar1     ar2      ma1      ma2      mean
##       0.0893  0.7369  -0.0738  -0.4474  286.3860
## s.e.  0.1313  0.1243   0.1692   0.1533   31.6835
## 
## sigma^2 = 22135:  log likelihood = -973.75
## AIC=1959.5   AICc=1960.08   BIC=1977.65
## 
## Training set error measures:
##                    ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE    MAPE      MASE
## Training set 1.493473 146.3124 114.5388 -37.09114 61.2933 0.6884333
##                      ACF1
## Training set -0.000863921

Explanation:

The ARIMA(2,0,2) model captures the short-term dynamics in my coffee sales data without needing difference. The second-lag auto regressive term is strong, indicating that sales from two days ago significantly influence todays sales. All information criteria (AIC, AICc, BIC) support this model as a good fit. Residuals show no autocorrelation, and MASE < 1 confirms that the model performs better than a nave benchmark. Overall, the ARIMA model is appropriate and provides reliable forecasts for my dataset.

2. Residual Analysis

res_arima <- residuals(fit_arima)
res_arima <- na.omit(res_arima)


plot(res_arima, main="Residuals (ARIMA)")

hist(res_arima, main="Histogram (ARIMA Residuals)")

acf(res_arima, main="ACF (ARIMA Residuals)")

3. Forecast Next 5 Periods

arima_forecast <- forecast(fit_arima, h=5)
arima_forecast
